# {{project-name | title_case}}

A jackdaw extension generated from the
[jackdaw-template-extension](https://github.com/jbuehler23/jackdaw_template_extension)
template.

## Build and install

1. Open jackdaw.
2. **File → Extensions → Build from project folder…**
3. Select this project's root directory.

Jackdaw runs `cargo build` with `RUSTC_WRAPPER=jackdaw-rustc-wrapper`
so the produced `.so` links against the editor's shared bevy
compilation. The resulting dylib is installed to
`~/.config/jackdaw/extensions/` (platform-specific) and live-loaded
immediately — your extension's windows, operators, and menu entries
become available the same frame.

## Editing

Put your extension logic inside `register`. `ExtensionContext`
exposes the registries (`register_window`, `register_operator`,
`register_menu_entry`, `register_panel_extension`). Each registration
is reversible — reloading the extension cleans up what the previous
version registered.

## Rebuild

Edit the code, save, click **Build from project folder…** again.
Future live-reload will do this automatically on source change.

## Why `bevy` is declared but the rlib is thrown away

Bevy's derive macros (`#[derive(Component)]`, `#[derive(Resource)]`)
read `CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR/Cargo.toml` at expansion time to figure
out how to name bevy's crate. `bevy = "0.18"` in `[dependencies]`
is just there so the macros emit correct paths. Cargo compiles
the real bevy into this project's `target/` on the first build,
but that `libbevy-<hash>.rlib` is never actually linked: jackdaw's
rustc wrapper rewrites `--extern bevy=<rlib>` to point at
`libjackdaw_sdk.so` so the TypeIds in your cdylib match the
editor's.

`jackdaw_api` isn't declared in Cargo.toml — the wrapper injects
its `--extern` flag unconditionally. `use bevy::prelude::*;`
reaches both bevy and jackdaw extension APIs through a single
unified prelude.
